## RQ2: Response Distribution Shape Recovery

For the primary outcome (`trust_multidimensional`), we compare response distributions of human and LLM clone participants within each of the 21 experimental conditions (control + 20 interventions).


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
conditions_all <- levels(human_data$condition)

dist_metrics <- map_dfr(conditions_all, function(cond) {
  compare_distributions(human_data, llm_data, "trust_multidimensional", cond)
})
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
source_colors <- c("Human" = "grey30", "LLM clone" = met.brewer("Juarez", n = 10)[1])

bind_rows(
  human_data |> select(condition, value = trust_multidimensional) |>
    mutate(source = "Human"),
  llm_data   |> select(condition, value = trust_multidimensional) |>
    mutate(source = "LLM clone")
) |>
  filter(!is.na(value)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = value, fill = source, color = source)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.35, linewidth = 0.4) +
  scale_fill_manual(values  = source_colors, name = NULL) +
  scale_color_manual(values = source_colors, name = NULL) +
  facet_wrap(~ condition, ncol = 4) +
  labs(x = "Multidimensional trust (0–100)", y = "Density") +
  plot_theme +
  theme(legend.position = "top")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Response distributions for multidimensional trust by experimental condition. Human participants shown in dark grey, LLM clones in orange.](preregistration_files/figure-html/fig-rq2-densities-1.png){#fig-rq2-densities width=2400}
:::
:::



::: {#tbl-rq2 .cell tbl-cap='RQ2 distribution comparison metrics by condition. OVL: overlapping coefficient (1 = identical). KS D: Kolmogorov–Smirnov D-statistic (0 = identical CDFs). Variance ratio: LLM clone / human variance.'}

```{.r .cell-code}
dist_metrics |>
  mutate(condition = factor(condition, levels = conditions_all)) |>
  arrange(condition) |>
  mutate(condition = as.character(condition)) |>
  gt() |>
  cols_label(condition = "Condition", ovl = "OVL",
             ks_d = "KS D", variance_ratio = "Variance ratio") |>
  fmt_number(columns = c(ovl, ks_d, variance_ratio), decimals = 3)
```

