## RQ4: Individual-level Demographic Calibration

RQ1–3 operate at the level of aggregated estimates (ATEs, interaction effects,
distributions). RQ4 asks whether clone responses are calibrated at the individual
level: do clones assigned a given demographic profile give responses that match what
real humans with those demographics give? All analyses below use the primary outcome
(`trust_multidimensional`) and the control condition unless stated otherwise.

### RQ4a: Demographic baseline calibration

For each of the six moderators, we compute mean outcomes within each demographic
group in the control condition separately for humans and clones, then correlate and
compare those cell means. High correlation and low RMSE indicate that clones have
the right baseline response level for each demographic type.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# Cell-mean comparison in the control condition, one moderator at a time
baseline_cal <- compare_demographic_baselines(
  human_data, llm_data,
  outcome    = "trust_multidimensional",
  moderators = moderators_cat
)
```
:::



::: {#tbl-rq4a .cell tbl-cap='Demographic baseline calibration. For each moderator, cell means in the control condition are compared between humans and clones. r: Pearson correlation of cell means. RMSE: root mean squared error. N cells: number of demographic groups.'}

```{.r .cell-code}
baseline_cal |>
  select(Moderator = moderator, r, RMSE = rmse, `N cells` = n_cells) |>
  gt() |>
  fmt_number(columns = c(r, RMSE), decimals = 3)
```

